<div class="tale">
	<h4>The Call of Oblivion</h4>
	<h5>By: Corwin of Amber</h5>
	<br>
	<div class="text"><b>The Call of Oblivion<br />
By Corwin of Amber</b><br />
<br />
<br />
	Corwin signed the last line of the missive to The Justice League.  Another fine Guild, another fine ally, he thought.  He stood up and walked out the door of his home near the Shrine of Justice.  He stood at the edge of the cliff, and closed his eyes.  It was so quiet, so peaceful here, with only the crashing waterfall disturbing the silence.  If only he could forget everything, and just lose himself here, in this most tranquil of places.  Alas, it was not meant to be.<br />
<br />
	Corwin felt the call, and it would not leave him.<br />
<br />
	He had too much work to do, truly, too much that required him to stay focused and in command of his thoughts.  He had responsibilities now, and people relied on him.  The Lost Order of Akalabeth was demanding, and required people with strength of spirit and devotion to the Light.  The Order would accept no less.<br />
<br />
	But still he felt the call.<br />
<br />
	This was a time of Strife for the Lost Order.  Many of the High Council secretly confessed their concerns to Corwin, and those words merely echoed the turmoil growing within him.  Oh, sure, there were countless fine Guilds who wished to ally themselves with Akalabeth, but double that number perceived the Guild to be a threat.  The swords of Power and Prominence have both double-edged blades... <br />
<br />
	Corwin opened his eyes, and looked across the expanse of the chasm before him.  Mist from the falls surrounded him, and light from torches of the Shrine swirled colors and shapes around him.  Somehow, in his pondering over the abyss, it had grown dark, and shadows played before his eyes, creeping through his gauntlets, hiding in the depths of his cape.  He needed to remain strong, to remain focused, for there was much to do.  He needed to ready himself for his audience with Freejack and Brimstone, and the rest of the Council.  He had reports to make, for his operatives had informed him that there were new players in the game.  The war with The Order of the Ebon Skull waged on, battles won, battles lost.  He needed to get word to the allies of Akalabeth, to the Mystical Knights of Avalon, to The Justice League, and to all the others, for the battle between the forces of Light and those of the Dark continued on, and would consume all.  Also, the new element, The Holy Disciples of the Guardian.  How would they play into all of this?<br />
<br />
	As he turned from the precipice of Justice, he stopped.  Somewhere in the mist, something was there, watching him.  Something of the Dark.<br />
<br />
	He was ill prepared for a battle, for he had left everything in his home, hours before.  With one last backward glance into the mists, he made his way home.<br />
<br />
	But Corwin heard the call one last time this day, uttered by the unknown Emissary of the Dark.  He heard it, and his soul shuddered at the voice.<br />
<br />
	"Corwin..." he heard, and the voice said, "...Oblivion..."<br />
<br />
<b><div style="text-align:center">The End</div></b></div>
	<br>
